TITLE: Russia’s Central Bank Raises Rates to 15 Percent to Curb Inflation
SUMMARY: The jump, from 13 percent, would bring a long period of “tight monetary conditions” in order to ease price pressures, the bank said.

TITLE: Consumers Kept Spending in September, as Inflation Held Steady
SUMMARY: Overall inflation stayed at 3.4 percent in September, down from a peak of around 7 percent.

TITLE: Ford’s U.A.W. Deal Will Raise Costs While Easing Labor Strife
SUMMARY: A tentative agreement gives union members at the carmaker their best terms in decades but could complicate Ford’s electric vehicle plans.

TITLE: U.S. Economic Growth Accelerated in the Third Quarter
SUMMARY: Gross domestic product expanded at a 4.9 percent annual rate over the summer, powered by prodigious consumer spending. But the pace is not expected to be sustained.

TITLE: Why U.A.W. President Shawn Fain Has Taken a Hard Line
SUMMARY: Shawn Fain owes his rise within the United Automobile Workers to a group determined to make the union far more confrontational toward automakers.

SUMMARY: The deal, subject to approval by union members, could ease the way for deals with General Motors and Stellantis and end a growing wave of walkouts.

TITLE: Biden Seeks to Tame Oil Prices if Mideast Conflict Sends Them Soaring
SUMMARY: The president has previously drawn down the Strategic Petroleum Reserve to ease price pressures, but that could be more difficult now

TITLE: U.A.W.’s Expanding Strikes Could Signal an Endgame or a Long Struggle
SUMMARY: The United Automobile Workers on Tuesday expanded its strike to General Motors’ largest U.S. plant a day after striking at a Ram truck plant.

SUMMARY: The carmaker said the six-week strike by the United Automobile Workers union had cost it $800 million so far and could cost $200 million for every week it continued.

TITLE: New Normal or No Normal? How Economists Got It Wrong for 3 Years.
SUMMARY: Economists first underestimated inflation, then underestimated consumers and the labor market. The key question is why.

SUMMARY: A new federal program will be a test of whether spreading funds outside of big cities will result in economic gains, or in inefficiencies.

TITLE: U.A.W. Expands Strike to a Ram Plant in Michigan
SUMMARY: The United Automobile Workers union called on 6,800 workers to walk off the job at a large factory that makes one of Stellantis’s most profitable vehicles.

TITLE: How High Interest Rates Sting Bakers, Farmers and Consumers
SUMMARY: Everyone who relies on credit in America is confronting a new reality: Money will cost more for a good long while.

SUMMARY: The United States is taking unusual action to clamp down on sales of chip-making machinery to China, even as Chinese firms are racing to stockpile the equipment.

SUMMARY: Pandemic stimulus, a strong job market and climbing stock and home prices boosted net worth at a record pace, Federal Reserve data showed.

SUMMARY: The executive chair of Ford Motor counsels patience as his company negotiates with the United Automobile Workers union, which has shut three of his company’s plants.

SUMMARY: The further limits on shipments could cripple Beijing’s A.I. ambitions and dampen revenues for U.S. chip makers, analysts said.

TITLE: A Higher Monthly Payment, but Less Square Footage
SUMMARY: Homebuilders are responding to rising interest rates with an innovation: a small house in the traditionally spacious exurbs.

TITLE: Those Doritos Too Expensive? More Stores Offer Their Own Alternatives.
SUMMARY: Retailers are expanding their own private-label food and beverage offerings, attracting customers looking for less expensive options.
